Nov 16 2009 	Still a favorite after four years	Since I wrote my initial review for The Ocean Park in 2006 (http://www.tripadvisor.com/ShowUserReviews-g60713-d291227-r5837277-Ocean_Park_Motel-San_Francisco_California.html), I've stayed there for the same event every September, and my delight in the place hasn't diminished a bit. Staying there is one of the highlights of my visit, and something I always look forward to.I recently had the opportunity to visit The Ocean Park in the company of my husband and teenage daughter when we drove up to San Francisco for a concert, which gave me the opportunity to experience more of the motel's amenities (and to see it through the eyes of my family, who had often heard me express my pleasure in the motel), which gives a fresh perspective, so on the advice of my husband, I'm writing another review.I had reserved a room with a queen bed and a twin, but was pleasantly surprised when we arrived to find that we'd been upgraded to one of the motel's small suites, with two queen beds, a full bath, a kitchenette and a dining room. As soon as we stepped into the room, my husband said &quot;wow...I'm impressed!&quot; I have to admit, I was too...I've always stayed in one of the smaller single queen rooms on the courtyard, which are lovely and comfortable, but small...this room was HUGE by motel standards! A small dining area branched off the main/sleeping room, connecting to a nice little kitchen that was better-equipped than any other self-catering accommodation I've stayed in. The bathroom featured a tub as well as a shower, with the deco styling I expect from The Ocean Park. The decor throughout was tasteful and attractive, featuring the diagonal wood paneling that is a hallmark of the motel, set off by soft peach and cream accents.We had plenty of time before we needed to get downtown for our concert, so my daughter immediately set off to enjoy the hot tub (which she says is &quot;really nice!&quot;), while my husband settled down for a nap, and I took the opportunity to read through the hand-outs they give you when you check in. I really wish more hotels/motels did this kind of thing! There was an extensive list of area restaurants, categorized by type, with directions how to get to each (including information on parking and public transit for those that weren't withing walking distance), directions via public transit to major tourist attractions, an area map, and even a suggested city tour using public transit that would hit the major tourist attractions in San Francisco.Speaking of public transit, a lot has been said here about the L-Taraval streetcar, which runs directly in front of The Ocean Park. Yes, it's there, and yes...if you're sensitive to such sounds, it can be noisy (it has never bothered me, even during this most recent stay, when we were in a room right on 46th...and my husband snoozed happily through several passes of the streetcar that afternoon). That said, it only runs until midnight. After that, the L line becomes a regular city bus, which is considerably quieter than the streetcar, and which only comes by a few times during the night. If a bus going by is going to bother you, you're unlikely to be happy in ANY lodging in San Francisco. But, if you are sensitive to sounds like this, and if you plan to be in bed before midnight, you can always request a room near the back of the motel when you make your reservation.We used the streetcar to get into the city center for our concert at The Fillmore, and it only took us 35 minutes to travel from the motel to Powell Street Station (near Union Square and the Cable Car Turntable) at 5 p.m. on a Friday. That's not bad travel time at all in a city of this size. If you're planning on a late night, you may want to make alternate plans for getting back, however. As I said, the streetcar becomes a bus after midnight, which is slower because it runs entirely on surface streets, and it runs much less frequently (about once an hour). In San Francisco, calling 511 will get you info on when and where you can catch it, but it's not a bad idea to have a city cab company's number on your cell phone, just in case you'd rather not wait. That's not going to be an issue, however, unless you're attending a late-night event.The other motel amenity that has gotten mention here is internet access. I do have to say that it can be pretty spotty. My understanding is that the 1930s construction (the very thing that gives the place much of its charm!) is to blame...some of the materials interfere with wireless reception. I've not been able to receive it in the single rooms. In our suite, my daughter was able to get a good connection with no trouble using her regular, full-size laptop, but my netbook just wasn't able to stay connected. The info they give you on check-in does offer suggestions for maximizing your chance of getting a connection, but if it is absolutely essential that you be able to connect to the internet in your motel room during your stay, this might not be the place for you. That said, a coffee place just up the block also has free wireless, so even if you can't get connected in your room, you're not entirely without recourse.What this all comes down to is that, after four years of staying at The Ocean Park, it remains one of my favorite motels in the world (and I've stayed in a lot of motels!). Unless you really need to be right in the middle of the city; or prefer cookie-cutter, plasticized, chain-motel lodgings; this is, in my opinion, the best place to stay on a budget in San Francisco.	
Nov 13 2009 	Fabulous Sunset Discovery	The Ocean Park motel is the best place to stay in the Sunset area of San Francisco without question. Quaint, clean and cozy, the staff went out of their way to accomodate our unique needs and it didn't take long for us to feel like we were staying with family. Some rooms come with kitchens and Noriega Market can supply all the ingredients but we also enjoyed lattes at Java Beach on Sloat and outstanding dinners at Outerlands Cafe on Judah. Public transportation is right there and Ocean beach is a short walk. Golden Gate Park is close by too. Great location, great prices and wonderful owners - we'll be back for sure!	
Nov 13 2009 	Best value in San Francisco	I stayed in this hotel with husband for one night.Rooms:It is hard to beat this motel in terms of value. The hotel rooms are nice and clean - ours was pretty large because that was all that was available on short notice. The bathrooms are on the small side, as this is a historic building. The beds were what you would expect for a motor inn; very clean but not 4-star hotel quality mattresses. The windows are original, so you may here some street noise (our room was toward the back of the hotel).Service: The desk clerk was very friendly, helpful and chatty. He let us know about great places to eat nearby (see below). We only stayed one night, so I can't comment on the quality of the housekeeping. The room was spotless when we arrived. Since this is a motor inn, other service items like a business center, room service, etc. are not provided. On the plus side, having free parking makes all of these short-comings worth it. Hotels in the city center charge an arm and a leg for parking.Location: The motel is located on the L-Taraval MUNI line that goes directly into the city center along Market St. (all the way to the Embarcadero). It is a relatively short walk to the San Francisco Zoo and a medium-length walk to get to the ocean front (bring a sweater!) Some other reviews mentioned the noise from the MUNI line, but I didn't notice. Compared with other cities of similar size, this motel is located in a relatively quiet area. Several blocks away (probably too long to walk) there are a few blocks of cheap, excellent restaurants serving primarily Asian cuisine. Bottom line:The hotel is an outstanding value, located in a relatively quiet residential area of San Francisco. If you have a car, want a low-cost place to stay, and don't mind driving a few minutes to get into the city center, this place is perfect. I probably would advise against staying here without a car - it is a longish ride on public transit to get to the city sights.	
