Oct 18 2008 	Why would you EVER want to stay downtown again!?!?!	I found this place on Tripadvisor after despairing of the current high cost of downtown accommodations. The Ocean Park is the perfect antidote: affordable, laid-back, uniquely charming, immaculately-kept, and smack-dab adjacent to one of the MUNI Metro lines that takes you directly into the Market Street subway. Furthermore, it's not only handy to San Francisco State Univ. and the airport, but within walking distance of the Zoo and the magnificent Pacific Ocean beach. It's easy to forget that the Ocean Park is 70+ years old. My second-floor room was both spacious and cozy; with a warm-colors decor, a flat-screen TV and an amazingly comfortable bed, a clean, bright black-and-white tiled bathroom and a full walk-in closet. Though it's true that there are only a couple walking-distance diners, there are some wonderful neighborhood resturants, including authentic Chinese, and the unique Bashfull Bull Too a short hop (via driving or trolley) away on Taraval. Being a guest here is like having a special refuge, out by the beach, to which you can retreat after spending a busy day in the city. I've stayed in many many places in San Francisco; from high-end Union Square hotels to independent 50s-era two-story motels. None has given me so much basic satisfaction as the Ocean Park Motel. Oddly enough, I recently found a photo of one of the MUNI trolleys that I'd taken while on a visit to the Zoo in 2000. I've attached it with this review, along with a similar shot from Sept. of 2008. Despite being so close, I missed out on staying at the Ocean Park while on that earlier visit. I know better now.	
Oct 4 2008 	I'm in Love with the Ocean Park Motel	I have been traveling the world for over 30 years. I've stayed in hundreds of hotels and motels, from scary tumble-down wrecks to five-diamond establishments in dozens of countries on four continents. I have never enjoyed a stay anywhere more than the Ocean Park Motel in San Francisco.A 1930's Art-Deco construction, this motel has been lovingly refurbished and updated by the couple who runs it. It is clearly a labor of love. My room in the inner courtyard, which is immaculately groomed, was obviously old construction, but spotlessly clean with everything in working order. The TV was a modern LCD flat-screen with functional remote and a more than adequate selection of cable channels. The bed was one of the most comfortable I have ever slept in, including my own - and that's saying a lot.The price was so reasonable - especially for San Francisco - that I thought I might have been undercharged.Location pros are a two-minute walk to the beach, a streetcar stop just outside the front door, and the San Francisco Zoo just across the street. Cons are a lack of other things to do or places to eat within walking distance - and a streetcar stop just outside the front door (the trolley noise might bother some people, but I didn't even notice it. The hotel thoughtfully provides wax earplugs on your night stand should this be a problem for you.)I plan on staying here again, and again, and again. I would recommend it to anyone who has a taste for something with much more charm and character than the run-of-the-mill paper-maché motel, and who doesn't mind staying in a place that evokes memories of an era tragically long-gone. Brass and glass you won't find, but in exchange you shall have an abundance of warmth and a personal touch that makes it seem much more like a home than a hotel.	
