Sep 18 2008 	Super Place	My wife and I stayed in the Ocean Park Motel for 8 nights in early September 2008. Our plan was to stay in one place, and go from there to visit central San Francisco by public transport and to spend two or three days touring the Napa Valley and places within easy driving distance from the city by car.We were very pleased that we decided to stay at Ocean Park. We had a room with a kitchen, and the overall cost was US $ 1,232 for 8 nights. (US $ 154 per night) We thought this was a bit expensive, but we did not want to stay in a seedy place, or pay a lot more for a hotel in central San Francisco. With the kitchen facility, it gave us the opportunity to relax, cook, or bring in take-away meals after the day’s sight-seeing, or go out to a restaurant for that matter. This was a saving and a nice flexible feature in itself.Our room was immaculately cleaned every day, and the kitchen had everything one needed: fridge with freezer, gas stove with oven, microwave, cutlery, plates, toaster, coffee maker, cups and glasses, and a table with two chairs.As other people have commented, Ocean Park is at the end of the Muni L streetcar line, and though it takes a half hour or so to get to downtown San Francisco, one can be always assured of getting a seat going, and if you have the time, can board it back at the other end of the line at Embarcadero station and get a seat on the way back, even in the rush hour.We had a rented car as well, and Ocean Park Motel is very conveniently located for travel by car across the Golden Gate Bridge to Napa valley to the north, or to Santa Cruz and beyond to the south, along the ocean-side highways. Most of downtown San Francisco traffic can be avoided.We were first time visitors to San Francisco from Nova Scotia, Canada. We researched Ocean Park Motel through its web site and through Tripadvisor and comments from previous visitors. We knew the price it would cost when we booked, and we were completely satisfied with what 